article.headline: Douglas continues to shine for Sun at home
article.linkText: Douglas, Sun cash in again at Mohegan arena
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- A bone chip in her left foot sidelined Katie Douglas for six games earlier this season and the Connecticut Sun shooting guard admits it's still not healed. But she looked plenty healthy to the Cleveland Rockers on Wednesday night, scoring 16 of her 23 points in the second half in the Sun's 64-57 victory at the Mohegan Sun casino. It was the second-highest point total in Douglas' two-year career and came one night after she was unable to get a shot off in Connecticut's 90-64 loss at New York. Sun coach Mike Thibault pulled her after 17 minutes against the Liberty. "He said he thought I just looked hesitant out there. I didn't practice for a couple of days," Douglas said. "I didn't come aggressive like I did tonight." Douglas had nine of Connecticut's first 12 points in the second half, including two straight 3s in the opening minutes. She finished 4-of-5 from behind the arc as Connecticut (7-8) snapped a three-game losing streak. It was Connecticut's fourth win at the casino, a home venue Douglas seems to shine in. She had a career-high 25 points in last week's 94-90 double-overtime loss to Indiana. "I wish we could play all the games here. I like the rims," she said. "It's just about being more comfortable out there." Nykesha Sales added 13 points for Connecticut and Brooke Wyckoff grabbed nine rebounds in her third start of the season. Chasity Melvin had 17 points and 10 rebounds for Cleveland (6-7), while rookie LaToya Thomas and Penny Taylor each scored eight points for the Rockers, who have lost four of five. The Rockers managed to wrap up speedy Sun guard Shannon Johnson, holding her to eight points, eight below her average. "We worked well on Johnson and Sales, but we didn't account for Douglas," Cleveland coach Dan Hughes said. Connecticut used runs of 6-2 and 5-0 to hold off Cleveland for most of the first half. Douglas had seven points in the half, including the Sun's only 3-pointer in the first five minutes of the game. The Sun led by as many as six points in the half until the Rockers put together a 7-0 run that featured a 3-pointer from Taylor to take a 19-17 lead with 6:33 left. The Sun regained the lead as Taj McWilliams-Franklin scored five of the next seven points for Connecticut, which led 28-25 at halftime. "I yelled at them yesterday for their lack of aggressiveness, but we did what we had to win tonight," Thibault said. "We have to win our games at home. All we wanted to do was take a positive step."

Game notes
Connecticut leads the series 2-1, with both teams winning at home. ... Johnson was selected as a reserve on the WNBA All-Star team with 35,087 votes. ... Cleveland guard Jennifer Rizzotti, a member of UConn's 1995 national championship team received an ovation during introductions.
